We have here 166 different observations with 7 variables. Gender and gender are demographical data from the participants of the test. Deep, stra and surf are numerical values which are derived through means of values of single questions. Attitude is scaled to fit the same Likert scale than deep, stra and surf questions. Points describes the number of points this individual received from the test. The participants are rather young.

Lets now investigate the characteristics of the data in form of plots:

library(ggplot2)

# plotted data
p1 <- ggplot(The_data, aes(x = attitude, y=points, col= gender))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")+
  ggtitle("points by gender in relation to attitude")

p2 <- ggplot(The_data, aes(x = age, y=attitude, col= gender))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")+
  ggtitle("Attitude by gender in relation to age")

p3 <- ggplot(The_data, aes(x = age, y = points, col = gender))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")+
  ggtitle("Points by gender in relation to age")

# Arrangements of the plots
ggpubr::ggarrange(
  plotlist = list(p1, p2, p3), labels = "AUTO",
  common.legend = T)

In the figure A you can see that in both male and female the points increase as the attitude rises. This effect however, is is stronger in males. In the figure B the attitude of males is slightly higher than in females in younger respondents. However, as we get closer to the 50 years of age, the number of observations decrease and the separation is not so clear anymore. Majority of the respondents are 20-35 years old. In the figure C you can see that the points of older men are clearly lower than younger men. This however is not observed with females.

Regression model

Then the regression model of the data:

library(GGally)
library(ggplot2)

my_model <- lm(points ~ attitude + deep + stra + surf, data = The_data)
summary(my_model)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = points ~ attitude + deep + stra + surf, data = The_data)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -16.7335  -3.1992   0.7975   3.4002  11.6582 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  15.4000     5.0245   3.065  0.00255 ** 
## attitude      3.4362     0.5739   5.987 1.34e-08 ***
## deep         -1.0072     0.7870  -1.280  0.20247    
## stra          0.8847     0.5411   1.635  0.10398    
## surf         -0.9105     0.8390  -1.085  0.27948    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.286 on 161 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.2154, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1959 
## F-statistic: 11.05 on 4 and 161 DF,  p-value: 6.057e-08

Based on the coefficients, the deep, stra and surf values does not statistically significantly predict the increase or decrease of the points in the test. However, attitude can predict the increase on test points (if none of the other variables are changed), as the p-value of the test is 1.34e-08. According to the model, one unit increase in attitude predict a 3.5 +/- 0.6 points better outcome than the latter attitude unit. However, as the residuals between the real value and the predicted value are quite high (maximum of 11.6, minimum of - 16.7 and a median of 0.79) the result should be interpreted within certain limits. This is further showed with a the R-squared value, which indeed is quite big (0.21).

Let’s observe this test data with figures. However, to make this more clear let’s make a new model where the deep, stra and surf variables are removed since the attitude data was the only significant variable in the model.

# simpler model
my_model1 <- lm(points ~ attitude, data = The_data)

#the residuals vs. fitted values, normal QQ, and residuals vs leverage plots
par(mar = c(4, 4, .1, .1))
plot(my_model1, which = c(1,2,5))

The linear model assumes linearity and a normally distributed residual. The model seems to meet the normality assumption, evident from the QQ-plot. Additionally, there’s consistent variance in errors, shown in the residual plot, and no points significantly impacting the model. In conclusion, the model effectively describes the relationship between the points and attitude.

That’s all folks!

The data consists of 370 observations and 36 columns. The data is a combination of two questionnaires from Portuguese secondary education. The data consists of binary/five-level answers. G1 is the first period grade, the G2 is the second period and the G3 is the final period grade (which is highly dependent of G1 and G2). The other column names corresponds to the variables asked from the students relating to their demographic and social and school related attributes.

Lets then perform some hypotheses of the correlation of alcohol use to other characteristics:

Students that goes out with friends a lot have higher alcohol consumption (variable “goout” numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 -very high) Students that have good quality family relationships have lower alcohol consumption (variable “famrel” numeric: from 1 - very bad to 5 - excellent) Students that have larger study time consumes less alcohol (variable “studytime” numeric: 1 - <2 hours, 2 - 2 to 5 hours, 3 - 5 to 10 hours, or 4 - >10 hours) Students that have better health status have lower alcohol comsumption (variable “health” numeric: from 1 - very bad to 5 - very good)

Let’s observe these correlations with a tabulation and plots:

From the box plots it seems that the boys and girls who go out with friends have higher alcohol use. Surprisingly, health status does not seem to be related with high alcohol use. Going out more and poor family relationships both seem to be associated with high alcohol consumption more than not. The study time does not seem to be associates with high alcohol consumption.

logistic regression

Let’s then explore the relationships between the variables with logistic regression:

# find the model with glm()
m <- glm(high_use ~ goout + famrel + health + studytime, data = alc, family = "binomial")

summary(m)
##

According to the model going out, family relationships and studytime can predict the high alcohol use in this model as the p value is significant at least at the 0.001 level. Let’s observe this further with odds ratios and confidence intervals:

# compute odds ratios (OR)
OR <- coef(m) %>% exp

# compute confidence intervals (CI)

CI <- confint(m) %>%exp

cbind(OR, CI)
##                    OR     2.5 %     97.5 %
## (Intercept) 3.6789255 0.8379073 16.7381578
## goout       0.4512833 0.3529115  0.5687263
## famrel      1.5148715 1.1531042  2.0005971
## health      0.8415759 0.6993355  1.0069611
## studytime   1.8120870 1.3178578  2.5415270

Odds ratios essentially indicate the predictive strength of explanatory variables. A value greater than 1 suggests that the variable is indicative of lower usage, while a value smaller than 1 suggests an association with high usage. In the case of health the OR is in both sides if 1 withing its confidence intervals, which means that its a poor predictor for alcohol use. On the other hand, going out is a good predictor of high usage and studytime and family relationships are both over 1 which means its a good indicator of low usage.

It seems that the model is not very good at predicting alcohol use, as it tends to predict too much high alcohol use. Lets still do a cross validation:

library(boot)
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}
# average of wrong predictions in the data

cv <- cv.glm(data = alc, cost = loss_func, glmfit = m, K = nrow(alc))

cv$delta[1]
## [1] 0.2621622

Average of wrong predictions with these variables is 0.262… or 26 %.

There is a high correlation between accessibility to radial highways (variable “rad”) and full-value property tax (variable “tax”). Which means that the homes closer to highways are more expensive. There is also an expected negative correlation between median value of owner occupied homes (variable “medv”) and lower status of the population (variable “lstat”). Which means that in the areas where the population have lower economic status the homes are also less valuable. There is also a strong negative correlation between the proportion on owner occupied homes built prior to 1940 (variable “age”) and the weighted mean distance to five Boston employment centers (variable “dis”), which means that the older owner-occupied houses are further away from the city center and Bostons services.

# plotting the analysis

lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.2, color = "black", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  graphics::arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)}

Next lets do a principal component analysis (PCA) on the data:

pca <- prcomp(human_, center = F, scale. = F)
sum <- summary(pca)

# biplot
pca_names <- round(100*sum$importance[2,], digits = 2)
biplot(pca, choices = 1:2, cex = c(0.6, 1), col = c("blue3", "red4"),
       xlabs = c(1:nrow(human)), xlab = paste0("PC1 (", pca_names[1], "%)"),
       ylab = paste0("PC2 (", pca_names[2], "%)"), sub = "GNI explains nearly all the variations" )

The variable GNI or Gross National Income per capita seems to explain all the variations in the data with this model. This is very weird, so lets try another approach by standardizing the data:

pca <- prcomp(human_, center = T, scale. = T)
sum <- summary(pca)
pca_names <- round(100*sum$importance[2,], digits = 2)
biplot(pca, choices = 1:2, cex = c(0.5, 1), col = c("blue", "red3"),
       #xlabs = c(1:nrow(human)),
       xlab = paste0("PC1 (", pca_names[1], "%)"),
       ylab = paste0("PC2 (", pca_names[2], "%)"), sub = "The variables in red on the left and right side of the plot are causing the majority of the variation")

Now the PCA looks more realistic. Now this is due to the mathematic formula the PCA follows. Standardizing the data for PCA ensures that all variables have the same scale, preventing variables with larger magnitudes from dominating the analysis, as seen in the first PCA. PCA is sensitive to the relative magnitudes of variables. Non-standardized data, may lead to biased results, as variables with larger scales could disproportionately influence the principal components. Standardization allows PCA to focus on the underlying patterns in the data, promoting a more equitable representation of each variable in the analysis.

The second PCA presented here accounts for 69% of the data’s variation, a substantial figure. PC1 contributes to 54% of this variation, demonstrating an inverse association with education and life expectancy while showing a direct link with maternal mortality and adolescent birth rate. Interestingly, these associations can be counter intuitive, as higher education levels often correlate with lower maternal mortality rates.

PC2, responsible for explaining 16% of the variation, is positively associated with female participation in society, encompassing the labor force and the percentage of females in parliament. A high PC2 value for a country suggests that females significantly influence society within that context.

Variables such as “labo.FM” (Labor Force Female/Male Ratio) and “Parl.E” (Percentage of Female Representatives in Parliament) play roles in illustrating these associations. In summary, the second PC sheds light on the impact of females on society through both their involvement in the workforce and political representation.

Ratssum <- Rats %>%
  filter(Time > 0) %>%
  group_by(Group, ID) %>%
  summarise( mean=mean(rats) ) %>%
  ungroup()

One of the means in group 2 is much higher compared to others so it will be brutally dropped as an outlier.

Ratssum1 <- Ratssum %>% filter(mean < 550)
ggplot(Ratssum1, aes(x = Group, y = mean)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  stat_summary(fun.y = "mean", geom = "point", shape=15, size=3, fill = "pink") +
  scale_y_continuous(name = "Adjusted mean weight")

Now this is better. Lets then check the significance between the groups with linear regression analysis:

library(dplyr)
library(tidyr)

# removing the outlier

RATS1 <- RATS[c(-12),]

# Add the baseline from the original data as a new variable to the summary data
Ratssum1 <- Ratssum1 %>% mutate(baseline = RATS1$WD1)
Ratssum <- Ratssum %>% mutate(baseline = RATS$WD1)

# Fit the linear model with the mean as the response 
fit <- lm(mean ~ baseline + Group, data = Ratssum1)
fit1 <- lm(mean ~ baseline + Group, data = Ratssum)


# Compute the analysis of variance table for the fitted model with anova()
anova(fit)

We can see from the anova results that there is significant differences between the means of the different groups (p = 0.0037). If the outlier would not have been removed, the significance would have been non significant at 0.05 alfa value. Therefore, its important to consider the outliers in the data prior to processing.
